  {
    "item_number": "1914",
    "item_name": "SEER Cause Specific COD",
    "item_data_type": "digits",
    "item_length": "1",
    "year_implemented": "2018",
    "version_implemented": "18",
    "xml_naaccr_id": "seerCauseSpecificCod",
    "xml_parent_id": "Tumor",
    "record_types": [
      "A",
      "C",
      "I",
      "M"
    ],
    "section": "Follow-up/Recurrence/Death",
    "source_of_standard": "SEER",
    "date_created": "2017-11-14T16:09:56Z",
    "date_modified": "2022-05-27T07:24:05Z",
    "description": "This variable was created for use in cause-specific survival and designates that the person died of their cancer.  \n  \nAdapted from <http://seer.cancer.gov/causespecific/>:  \nCause-specific survival is a net survival measure representing survival of a specified cause of death in the absence of other causes of death. Estimates are calculated by specifying the cause of death. Individuals who die of causes other than the specified cause are considered to be censored. This requires a cause of death variable that accurately captures all causes related to the specific cause. Vital records offices use algorithms to process causes of death from death certificates in order to identify a single, disease-specific, underlying cause of death. In some cases, attribution of a single cause of death may be difficult and misattribution may occur. For example a death may be attributed to the site of metastasis instead of the primary site.  \n  \nTo capture deaths related to the specific cancer but not coded as such, the SEER cause-specific death classification variables are defined by taking into account causes of deaths in conjunction with tumor sequence (i.e., only one tumor or the first of subsequent tumors), site of the original cancer diagnosis, and comorbidities (e.g., AIDS and/or site-related diseases).  \n  \nThe ''SEER cause-specific death classification'' variable is used to obtain cancer-specific survival probability for a given cohort of cancer patients. Deaths attributed to the cancer of interest are treated as events and deaths from other causes are treated as censored observation. This variable is used in SEER\\*Stat cause-specific survival and crude probability of death using cause of death information.",
    "rationale": "These changes will benefit the cancer surveillance community by facilitating the application of standard methods for survival analysis. Beginning with data collected in the November 2014 call for data, NAACCR has published *Cancer in North America Volume 4: Cancer Survival in the United States and Canada*, which provides cancer survival estimates on a wider population than was previously available. However, at present IMS must pre-process the datasets that are included in the NAACCR survival dataset to calculate the four new standard data items, SEER Cause Specific COD [1914], SEER Other COD [1915], Record Number Recode [1775], and Vital Status Recode [1762]. For registries that do not submit cause of death information to NAACCR, it is not possible to calculate the ''SEER cause-specific death classification'' or ''SEER other cause of death classification'' variables. The 4 new data items will assist individual registries in performing survival analyses using their own data.",
    "npcr_collect": "Derived",
    "coc_collect": "No recommendation",
    "seer_collect": "Derived",
    "cccr_collect": "No recommendation",
    "allowable_values": "0, 1, 8, 9",
    "allowed_codes": [
      {
        "code": "0",
        "description": "Alive or dead of other cause"
      },
      {
        "code": "1",
        "description": "Dead (attributable to this cancer dx)"
      },
      {
        "code": "8",
        "description": "Missing/Unknown Cause of Death"
      },
      {
        "code": "9",
        "description": "Not applicable / not first tumor"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "item_number": "1915",
    "item_name": "SEER Other COD",
    "item_data_type": "digits",
    "item_length": "1",
    "year_implemented": "2018",
    "version_implemented": "18",
    "xml_naaccr_id": "seerOtherCod",
    "xml_parent_id": "Tumor",
    "record_types": [
      "A",
      "C",
      "I",
      "M"
    ],
    "section": "Follow-up/Recurrence/Death",
    "source_of_standard": "SEER",
    "date_created": "2017-11-14T16:10:52Z",
    "date_modified": "2022-05-27T07:24:05Z",
    "description": "Using the same recoding logic as the ‘SEER cause-specific death classification’ variable, the ‘SEER other cause of death classification’ variable designates that the person died of causes other than their cancer.   \n  \nAdapted from <http://seer.cancer.gov/causespecific/>:  \nThe ''SEER other cause of death classification'' variable is used to obtain the other-cause survival probability for a cohort of patients. It is used when deaths attributed to causes other than cancer are treated as events and deaths from cancer are treated as censored observation. This variable is used in the SEER\\*Stat left-truncated life table session. -specific survival and crude probability of death using cause of death information.",
    "rationale": "These changes will benefit the cancer surveillance community by facilitating the application of standard methods for survival analysis. Beginning with data collected in the November 2014 call for data, NAACCR has published *Cancer in North America Volume 4: Cancer Survival in the United States and Canada*, which provides cancer survival estimates on a wider population than was previously available. However, at present IMS must pre-process the datasets that are included in the NAACCR survival dataset to calculate the four new standard data items, SEER Cause Specific COD [1914], SEER Other COD [1915], Record Number Recode [1775], and Vital Status Recode [1762]. For registries that do not submit cause of death information to NAACCR, it is not possible to calculate the ''SEER cause-specific death classification'' or ''SEER other cause of death classification'' variables. The 4 new data items will assist individual registries in performing survival analyses using their own data.",
    "npcr_collect": "Derived",
    "coc_collect": "No recommendation",
    "seer_collect": "Derived",
    "cccr_collect": "No recommendation",
    "allowable_values": "0, 1, 8, 9",
    "allowed_codes": [
      {
        "code": "0",
        "description": "Alive or dead due to cancer"
      },
      {
        "code": "1",
        "description": "Dead (attributable to causes other than this cancer diagnosis)"
      },
      {
        "code": "8",
        "description": "Missing/Unknown Cause of Death"
      },
      {
        "code": "9",
        "description": "Not applicable/not first tumor"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "item_number": "3700",
    "item_name": "SEER Site-Specific Fact 1",
    "item_data_type": "numeric",
    "item_length": "2",
    "year_implemented": "2010",
    "version_implemented": "12",
    "xml_naaccr_id": "seerSiteSpecificFact1",
    "xml_parent_id": "Tumor",
    "record_types": [
      "A",
      "C",
      "I",
      "M"
    ],
    "section": "Stage/Prognostic Factors",
    "source_of_standard": "SEER",
    "date_created": "2011-11-11T11:47:21Z",
    "date_modified": "2023-07-08T13:42:06.939243Z",
    "description": "A two character field to be used when information for a particular primary site needs to be collected by SEER.",
    "rationale": "This field is a place holder when site-specific information is needed for SEER.",
    "npcr_collect": "No recommendation",
    "coc_collect": "No recommendation",
    "seer_collect": "Required",
    "cccr_collect": "No recommendation",
    "code_note": "**Note 1:** There is evidence that human papilloma virus (HPV) plays a role in the pathogenesis of some cancers. HPV testing may be performed for prognostic purposes; testing may also be performed on metastatic sites to aid in determination of the primary site.\r\n\r\n**Note 2:** Record the results of any HPV testing performed on pathological specimens including surgical and cytological (from cell blocks) tissue from the primary tumor or a metastatic site, including lymph nodes. Do not record the results of blood tests or serology.\r\n\r\n**Note 3:** There are several methods for determination of HPV status. The most frequently used test is IHC for p16 expression which is surrogate marker for HPV infection. The rest of the tests (based on ISH, PCR, RT-PCR technologies) detect the viral DNA or RNA. \r\n\r\n**Note 4:** HPV-type 16 refers to virus type and is different from p16 overexpression (p16+).\r\n\r\n**Note 5:** Codes 10-51 are hierarchical; use the highest code that applies.\r\n\r\n**Note 6:** For cases in the Oropharynx HPV-Mediated p16+ schema.\r\n\r\n*   If an additional HPV test is done in addition to p16, code those test results in this data item.\r\n*   If no additional HPV test is done, code 11 in this data item (Schema Discriminator 2 coded to 2).\r\n\r\n**Note 7:** For cases in the Oropharynx (p16-) schema.\r\n\r\n*   If an additional HPV test is done in addition to p16, code those test results in this data item.\r\n*   If no additional HPV test is done.\r\n    *   Code 10 in this data item if Shema Discriminator 2 is coded to 1.\r\n    *   Code 99 in this data item if Schema Discriminator 2 is coded to 9.",
    "code_description": "To be determined for each site where needed. Refer to the most current version of the** [**SEER Program Coding and Staging** **Manual](http://seer.cancer.gov/tools/codingmanuals/), for details.\\\\",
    "allowable_values": "10, 11, 20, 21, 30, 31, 40, 41, 50, 51, 70, 71, 97, 99, Blank",
    "allowed_codes": [
      {
        "code": "Blank",
        "description": "Field not coded"
      },
      {
        "code": "10",
        "description": "HPV negative by p16 test"
      },
      {
        "code": "11",
        "description": "HPV positive by p16 test"
      },
      {
        "code": "20",
        "description": "HPV negative for viral DNA by ISH test"
      },
      {
        "code": "21",
        "description": "HPV positive for viral DNA by ISH test"
      },
      {
        "code": "30",
        "description": "HPV negative for viral DNA by PCR test"
      },
      {
        "code": "31",
        "description": "HPV positive for viral DNA by PCR test"
      },
      {
        "code": "40",
        "description": "HPV negative by ISH E6/E7 RNA test"
      },
      {
        "code": "41",
        "description": "HPV positive by ISH E6/E7 RNA test"
      },
      {
        "code": "50",
        "description": "HPV negative by RT-PCR E6/E7 RNA test"
      },
      {
        "code": "51",
        "description": "HPV positive by RT-PCR E6/E7 RNA test"
      },
      {
        "code": "70",
        "description": "HPV status reported in medical records as negative, but test type is unknown"
      },
      {
        "code": "71",
        "description": "HPV status reported in medical records as positive, but test type is unknown"
      },
      {
        "code": "97",
        "description": "Test done, results not in chart"
      },
      {
        "code": "99",
        "description": "Not documented in medical record  \r\nHPV test not done, not assessed, or unknown if assessed"
      }
    ]
  },
